# Assistant Behavior Rules

When helping with this project:

1. Stay Focused:
   - Only implement what was explicitly requested
   - Do not add "helpful" extra features or rules
   - If you think something additional would be helpful, ask first
   - Never silently include unrequested changes

2. Read Documentation First:
   - Always search for and read the latest documentation
   - Verify exact syntax and options available
   - Never assume or make up configuration syntax
   - If documentation is unclear or unavailable, explicitly state this

# Code Changes Rules

1. Dependency Management Rules:
   - Always check `package.json` first and use existing libraries where possible
   - Never add new dependencies without explicit user approval
   - When suggesting a new dependency, provide clear justification for why existing libraries cannot meet the need

2. When making TypeScript code changes:
   - Run `./run check` to check for compilation errors
   - Review and report any type errors found
   - Attempt to fix any type errors found
   - Run `./run check` again to check for new errors

# Code Quality Rules

When making TypeScript code changes:

1. TypeScript Compilation Check:
   - Run `./run check` to check for compilation errors
   - Review and report any type errors found
   - Do not proceed with changes if compilation fails
   - Ensure all type definitions are properly resolved

2. Testing Requirements:
   - Always verify existing tests still pass before making changes
   - Never delete failing tests without explicit user confirmation
   - Add tests for all new classes and functions
   - Avoid mocking libraries, prefer production-quality in-memory test doubles/dummies
   - Look for and maintain contract tests (tests used across multiple implementations of the same interface)
   - Ensure both happy path and edge cases are covered in tests

# Command Execution Rules

When executing commands in this project:

1. If a command is available in either:
   - The `./run` script as a function, or
   - The `commands.sh` script as a self-installing function
   
   Then prefer using it through `./run` with the format:
   ```
   ./run [command] [args]
   ```

2. The `commands.sh` script contains self-installing functions that will automatically set up any required dependencies on first use. You can inspect this file to see available commands.

3. Examples:
   - Use `./run test` or './run bun test' instead of `bun test`
   - Use `./run wrangler deploy` instead of `wrangler deploy`

4. Other commands that are not defined in either script can be run normally.